Part I - Prosper Loan Data Dataset Exploration¶

by Joshua Enam Semanyoh¶

Introduction¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan; including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, employment status, listing category, term, prosper rating and many other variables.

According to this official Prosper website article, https://www.prosper.com/invest/how-to-invest/prosper-ratings/?mod=article_inline#:~:text=The%20Prosper%20Rating%20is%20our,average%20annualized%20loss%20rate%20range. the prosper rating (which denotes level of risk associated with a loan application or estimated average annualized loss rate range) is ordered this way from worst (HR) to best (AA).

In [22]:
# Convert 'ProsperRating (Alpha)' into an ordered categorical datatype from worst to best

prosper_rating = ['HR', 'E', 'D', 'C', 'B', 'A', 'AA']
p_rating = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True, categories=prosper_rating);
prosper['ProsperRating (Alpha)'] = prosper['ProsperRating (Alpha)'].astype(p_rating);

A bit of wrangling was done on the dataset to get it ready for exploratory data analysis¶

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan; including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, employment status and many other variables.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main feature of the dataset that I am most interested in is the Borrower APR.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

According to this CNBC article, https://www.cnbc.com/select/what-factors-lenders-consider-when-determining-apr/ I have deduced the following features will greatly help in the investigation of Borrower APR/ Borrower rate. They are loan original amount, stated monthly income, term, Prosper rating (alpha), employment status, listing category, credit score (credit score range lower), payment history*, borrower state** (for mortgages), debt to income ratio. I will consider most of them in my investigation.

Univariate Exploration¶

I'll begin by exploring the main feature of interest: BorrowerAPR¶

In [24]:
# Plot a hist for BorrowerAPR with bins
bins = np.arange(0.04, prosper['BorrowerAPR'].max()+0.05, 0.01)
plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
plt.hist(data = prosper, x = 'BorrowerAPR', bins=bins);
plt.xlabel('BorrowerAPR');

The plot appears to be multimodal. Close to 0.1 there is a small peak, right on both sides of 0.2 there are two more peaks and another peak close to 0.3 mark. There is a very high peak at 0.36. The plot shows that very few Borrower APRs are more than 0.4, not more than 100.

Next, I'll explore the variables LoanOriginalAmount and StatedMonthlyIncome¶

The top three most common original loan amount is 4000, followed by 15000, then 10000. The highest loan amount is 35000 and the lowest is 1000; both of which are the least frequent amounts. We can see that more than half of the original loan amounts are 10000 and below.

The minimum wage per month in US has been at least more than 500 dollars since 1980 and over 1000 dollars since 2009. For the purpose of this analysis, let's consider only borrowers with stated monthly income between 1000 and 15000 dollars.

In [26]:
# Return Stated Monthly Income between 1000 and 15000
prosper = prosper[prosper.StatedMonthlyIncome>= 1000]
prosper = prosper[prosper.StatedMonthlyIncome<= 15000]

prosper = prosper.reset_index(drop=True)

What is the most common loan term?¶

In [29]:
# Function for countplot distributions
def count_plot(data, column_name):
    plt.figure(figsize=[9,6])
    data = prosper
    base_color = sns.color_palette()[0]
    ax = sns.countplot(x = prosper[column_name], color = base_color)
    plt.xticks(rotation=40)
    plt.xlabel(column_name.title())
    plt.show()
    
count_plot(prosper, 'Term');

The most frequent loan term is 36 months

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The distribution of borrowers' APR looks multimodal. Majority of the values are within the range of 0.05 and 0.4. There is a very high peak at 3.6. However, there are no unusual points that require any transformations.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The descriptive statistics showed that stated monthly income variable had some unusually high values (outliers). I cleaned the data removing the outliers (as high monthly incomes such as 400,000 had loan amounts of 2000 nd monthly payment plans under 100 dollars) and created a new range from 1000 to 15000 dollars for the purpose of the analysis, which was seen to be multimodal.

Bivariate Exploration¶

In this section, I investigate relationships between Borrower APR against other related variables (quantitative and qualitative). Then I explore other interesting variables.

Explore the relationship between Borrower APR and both Original Loan Amount and Stated Monthly Income.¶

In [37]:
# Scatter plot of Borrower APR against Original Loan Amount
plt.figure(figsize=[20, 5])

plt.subplot(1,2,1)
plt.scatter(data=prosper, y='BorrowerAPR', x='LoanOriginalAmount', alpha=1/20);
plt.ylabel('Borrower APR');
plt.xlabel('Original Loan Amount');

# Scatter plot of Borrower APR against Stated Monthly Income
plt.subplot(1,2,2)
plt.scatter(data=prosper, y='BorrowerAPR', x='StatedMonthlyIncome', alpha=1/20);
plt.ylabel('Borrower APR');
plt.xlabel('Stated Monthly Income $');

From the left plot we see that as the loan amount increases the borrower APR range becomes smaller. We observe that loan amounts between 30000 and 35000 have an APR between the range of 0.10 and 0.20.

From the right plot we see that monthly incomes do not seem to really have a strong and clear effect on the APRs. We can use heatmap to explore this further.

Use a heatmap to explore Borrower APR and Stated Monthly Income further¶

In [38]:
plt.hist2d(data=prosper, x='StatedMonthlyIncome', y='BorrowerAPR', cmin=0.5, cmap='viridis_r');
plt.colorbar()
plt.xlabel('Stated Monthly Income, $');
plt.ylabel('Borrower APR');

We see from the heatmap that stated monthly income doesn't have a clear correlation with Borrower APR just as with the scatterplot. However we also see that for incomes between 4000 and 6000, the most frequent APR offered is in the range of 0.12 and 0.22.

Explore relationship between Borrower APR and some categorical variables. Further explore relationship between other numeric and categorical variables.¶

How does Prosper Rating affect Borrower APR?¶

In [39]:

In [40]:

plt.figure(figsize=[8,5]);
sns.boxplot(data=prosper, x='ProsperRating (Alpha)', y='BorrowerAPR', color=base_color);

There is a strong correlation between Prosper rating and Borrower APR. The better the Prosper rating, the lower the APR. The median APR for Borrower's with Prosper rating AA is 0.10, although there are some outliers. Overall, the median APR decreases with respect to Prosper Rating from the worst HR to the best rating AA.

The median and maximum value of stated monthly incomes increases with better Prosper ratings. Also, median of loan amounts increased with improving Prosper ratings (from HR to C) and was then observed to be the same from C to AA. The maximum loan amounts increased from HR to AA.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

From the scatterplot exploring relationship between borrower APR and loan amount we see that as the loan amount increases the borrower APR range becomes smaller. We observe that loan amounts between 30000 and 35000 have an APR between the range of 0.10 and 0.20.

Using the heatmap and scatterplot we see that stated monthly income doesn't have a clear correlation with Borrower APR, however from the heatmap we observe that for incomes between 4000 and 6000, the most frequent APR offered is in the range of 0.12 and 0.22.

There is a strong correlation between Prosper rating and Borrower APR. The better the Prosper rating, the lower the APR. The median APR for Borrower's with Prosper rating AA is 0.10, although there are some outliers. Overall, the median borrower APR decreases with respect to Prosper Rating from the worst HR to the best rating AA.

Those employed had a lower (better) median borrower APR, although the minimum and maximum APR values for the employed are still 0.5 and 4.2 respectively.

The median borrowed APRs for all loan terms are very close (a little over the 0.20 mark).

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

The median and maximum value of stated monthly incomes increases with better Prosper ratings. Also, median of loan amounts increased with improving Prosper ratings (from HR to C) and was then observed to be the same from C to AA. The maximum loam amounts increased from HR to AA.

Those employed had a lower (better) median borrower APR, although the minimum and maximum APR values for the employed are still 0.5 and 4.2 respectively. Those employed and in full-time as well had the highest median incomes and highest maximum monthly incomes which is expected. Also those employed had the highest median loan amounts and highest maximum loan amounts.

The most common loan term for all Prosper ratings is 36 months. Interestingly, there is only 36 months loans for HR rating borrowers.

The stated monthly income increases with better ratings for all terms. Interestingly though, for 12 month term, the stated income doesnt fall below 5000 for the worst ratings. Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

Yes, as loan term increases the APR range reduces as the loan amount increases.

Overall, borrower APR reduces with increasing Prosper rating even as loan amount increases. However, when taking very high loans for A and AA ratings, there is observed to be a slightly higher APR than usual for A and AA ratings which is against the overall trend.

We also observed that the borrower APR decreases with the increasing loan term for borrowers with HR to C ratings. However, for people with B to AA ratings, the borrower APR increases with increasing loan term.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Interesting to note, it is observed that for 12-month term, the stated monthly income doesn't fall below 5000 dollars for the worst ratings as it does for the other loan terms. This may be an indication that for 12-month term, borrowers need to have a baseline monthly income of at least 5000.

Another interesting observation is that loans are capped below 6000 for borrowers taking a 12-month loan regardless of their ratings. This is not same for 36 and 60-month loans.

Conclusions¶

  1. The main findings from the exploratory visualization is that borrower APR is affected by the loan amount; it is seen that as loan amount increases the borrower APR range becomes smaller.

  2. Prosper Rating has a strong effect on Borrower APR; with improving Prosper rating there is lower Borrower APR. Even as the loan amount increases, this general trend is still evident. However, when borrower with the best two Prosper ratings are taking very high loans, their APR is slightly increased. This may be to deter highly rated borrowers from taking higher loans since other plots also showed that borrowers with the best ratings generally take higher loans. It may also be that Prosper (lending company) wants to make profit since a slight increase in APR on a high loan is still very substantial.

  3. Another finding is that for very highly rated borrowers, their APR increases when they choose a longer loan term. However, for borrowers with ratings from HR to C, their APR reduces if they choose a longer term.

  4. Another finding is that borrowers taking a short term loan (12-month) must have a baseline monthly income of 5000 dollars if they are rated D to HR whereas this doesn't apply to longer terms.

  5. Short term (12-month) loans are capped below 6000 dollars regardless of Prosper rating of the borrower.
